# Reuse shared code before duplicating it

- **Search first**: Before writing a helper, look for existing utilities, hooks, services, or types that already solve the problem.
- **Extract on the third copy**: Two similar snippets can be a coincidence; three is a signal—lift the shared idea into one place.
- **Pick the right home**: Place shared code in an existing module or a clearly named `*/shared/`, `*/lib/`, or `*/utils/` boundary—never deep inside an unrelated feature.
- **Narrow surface**: Export a small, well-named function or type rather than a grab-bag “helpers” module. Hidden coupling is worse than a little duplication.
- **Composition > copy-paste**: Prefer composing existing functions/components/hooks; pass parameters instead of forking near-identical variants.
- **Avoid premature abstraction**: If two cases will likely diverge, keep them separate until the shared shape is obvious. Re-evaluate when the third caller appears.
- **Update call sites**: When you extract, replace the duplicates—don’t leave stale copies that drift.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD: same logic copy-pasted across files
function totalA(items: Item[]) { return items.reduce((s, i) => s + i.priceCents, 0); }
function totalB(rows: Item[])  { return rows.reduce((s, r) => s + r.priceCents, 0); }

// ✅ GOOD: one shared, well-named function reused everywhere
export function sumPriceCents(items: readonly Item[]): number {
  return items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.priceCents, 0);
}
```
